... this is a huge digression, but:

One thing that is quite a drawback with the ansible templates is that we don't have any way to "render" out the example templates for manual modification.

For example, my templates for overcloud deployment with Ironic: https://github.com/hjensas/homelab/tree/master/labs/ovb-ironic-overcloud/overcloud/nic-configs

It uses custom network Baremetal, creating those multi-nic templates was easy by using roles_data and network_data as input to the process_templates.py tool. Then all I had to do was change the nic: entries.

In the real world users typically won't use 'nic: nicX', they would reference the hardware interface name i.e 'nic: em2' 'nic: enp2p1' etc.

Is there are way to get jinja2 to only substitute the loop var's? i.e get code like this:

  {% for network in [netA, netB, netC] %}
  - nic: nic{{ loop.index + 1 }}
  - mtu: {{ lookup('vars', networks_lower[network] ~ '_mtu') }}
  {% endfor %}

to render:

  - nic: nic1
    mtu: {{ lookup('vars', networks_lower['netA'] ~ '_mtu') }}
  - nic: nic2
    mtu: {{ lookup('vars', networks_lower['netB'] ~ '_mtu') }}
  - nic: nic3
    mtu: {{ lookup('vars', networks_lower['netC'] ~ '_mtu') }}

Then all I'd need to do was edit it manually to set the nic's, like:

  - nic: enp3p1
    mtu: {{ lookup('vars', networks_lower['netA'] ~ '_mtu') }}
  - nic: enp1p2
    mtu: {{ lookup('vars', networks_lower['netB'] ~ '_mtu') }}
  - nic: enp1p1
    mtu: {{ lookup('vars', networks_lower['netC'] ~ '_mtu') }}

